Secondary metabolites are usually biosynthesized as single stereoisomers in nature, but some natural products exist as enantiomers (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

, 

). As stereocentres in structures often determine biological and pharmaceutical properties together with chemical and physical characteristics, it is very important to chirally separate enantiomers and establish their absolute configurations. Enantiomers can usually be separated by chiral columns, but suitable or new approaches can be used or developed to separate enantiomers with limited amounts. Recently, our group initiated the chemical investigation of desert plant endophytic fungi from Northwest 
China
considering their special bioenvironments and few chemical investigations. A series of new secondary metabolites with diverse biological activities were isolated from this group of fungi (

, 

; 

; 

, 

; 

). Per our ongoing research to mine secondary metabolites with unique structures and potential bioactivities from this special group of fungi, the EtOAc extracts of the endophytic fungus 
Phaeosphaeriaceae
sp. were investigated, which led to the isolation of a novel polyketide-originated secondary metabolite, phaeosphspirone (
1
), and two known pyranonaphthoquinones, herbarin (
2
) and 
O
-methylherbarin (
3
) (
Fig. 1
) (

). A pair of enantiomers (
1
/ 
1
′
) existing in phaeosphspirone were separated by HPLC chromatography after derivatization with Mosher’ s reagents, and the absolute configurations of 
1
/ 
1
′
were simultaneously determined according to Mosher’ s rule. This tandem strategy provides a useful approach for the separation and stereochemical determination of enantiomers with secondary hydroxyl groups. In this report, the structural elucidation, separation, possible biogenetic pathway, and biological activities of these compounds are presented.

To support this conclusion, computer-assisted structure elucidation (CASE) was used to analyse the NMR data of phaeosphspirone. CASE, as a technological development, was developed in recent years to overcome obstacles in NMR data interpretation (
,
;
;
;
). ACD/Structure Elucidator was used to resolve the uncertain connection of C-4 with C-12, which gave 519 candidates filtered from 126,650 isomers in 2 min 2 s from the MCD (molecular connectivity diagram). The top ten candidates were generated by ACD/Structure Elucidator. Structure ranking is based on the overall differences between experimental and predicted 13 C chemical shifts ( Fig. 3 ). The lower the value ( dN ( 13 C)-neural network and dA ( 13 C)-HOSE), the better the ranking. Atom colour coding is based on the individual atom difference between experimental and predicted 13 C chemical shifts. The green colour represents a difference between 0 and 3 ppm, and the yellow colour is > 3–15 ppm. Structures ranking 1–4 display “the same flat structures” as that of phaeosphspirone but with different atom/NMR shift assignments. Thus, according to the calculated CASE results together with NMR data analysis, the planar structure of phaeosphspirone was established.

The relative configuration of phaeosphspirone was determined by NOE spectra analysis (
Fig. 2
). Upon irradiation with H-3, enhancements of 12-OMe and 1-Me were observed, while irradiation with 12-OMe or 1- Me led to the enhancement of 1-Me and H-3 or H-3 and 12-OMe, respectively. These results confirmed that 1-Me, H-3 and 12-OMe had the same orientation on the furan ring, which established the relative configuration of phaeosphspirone (Fig. S11-S13).

The optical rotation of phaeosphspirone was near zero, implying that a pair of enantiomers ( 1 / 1 ′ ) might exist for this compound. It was difficult to obtain enough enantiomers by chiral column separation due to the limited amounts of enantiomers ( 1 / 1 ′ ). Considering a secondary hydroxyl group in the structure of phaeosphspirone, if chiral reagents (such as Mosher’ s reagents) are mixed with phaeosphspirone ( 1 / 1 ′ ), theoretically, two diastereomers would be generated, which could then be separated using an HPLC column (C 18 ). This approach could also determine the stereochemistry of C-3 based on Mosher’ s rule. Reactions of phaeosphspirone ( 1 / 1 ′ ) with ( R )-MTPA-Cl will form the corresponding S -MTPA ester ( 1a and 1 ′ a ), and reactions of phaeosphspirone ( 1 / 1 ′ ) with ( S )-MTPA-Cl will form the corresponding R -MTPA ester ( 1b and 1 ′ b ) (
). As expected, two peaks were observed in the corresponding HPLC profiles (Supporting Information ). This demonstrated that a pair of enantiomers existed in phaeosphspirone. According to Mosher’ s rule, the difference in chemical shifts (Δ
δSR
=
δS - δR
) for 1a and 1b assigned the C- 3 in 1 / 1 ′ to be S / R ( Fig. 4 ).

Considering the coisolation of herbarin (
2
) and 
O
-methylherbarin (
3
) from the same fungus and the similar structural features, phaeosphspirone (
1
/ 
1
′
) is likely to be derived from 
2
with a pyranonaphthoquinone core skeleton. Isotopic enrichment experiments revealed that pyranonaphthoquinone scorpinone coisolated with 
2
from the same fungus originating from polyketide biosynthesis (

), and Tudzynski et al. investigated the biosynthetic polyketide (PKS) gene cluster of fusarubin, a pyranonaphthoquinone analogue similar to scorpinone (

). This evidence supported that phaeosphspirone, as a heptaketide, was biosynthesized from a PKS pathway similar to the metabolites mentioned above. Polyketides (PKSs) can be further divided into the following three subtypes: nonreduced (NR), partially reduced (PR), and highly reduced (HR), which are biosynthesized from the corresponding mega-synthase NR-PKS synthases (NR-PKSs), PR-PKSs and HR-PKSs, respectively (Fig. S18) (

).

The structural features of herbarin ( 2 ), O -methylherbarin ( 3 ) and phaeosphspirone imply that compounds 1–3 originate from nonreducing polyketide synthases (NR-PKSs) (
). The genome of this fungus was then sequenced and shown to possess eight reducing polyketide synthase (HR-PKSs and PR-PKSs) and four nonreducing polyketide synthase (NR-PKS) gene clusters. Bioinformatics and phylogenetic analysis revealed that an NR-PKS gene cluster in scaffold3 ( sgp cluster) of Phaeosphaeriaceae sp. is hypothesized to be the polyketide product (phaeosphspirone) of
Fusarium fujikuroi
fsr1 (gene cluster of fusarubin) ( Fig. 5 and Fig. S18-S20). The multimodular polyketide synthases fsr1 and sgpC have the same domains, including SAT, KS, AT, PT, ACP and R. Further analysis of the conserved active sites of fsr1 and sgpC shows that these domains are all active (Fig. S21). The predicted proteins in the sgp cluster include SgpC (NR-PKSs), SgpB and SgpF ( O -methyltransferases); SgpE (cytochrome P450 monooxygenase); and two Baeyer Villiger monooxygenase (DUF4243) family oxidases (SgpA and SgpG), which are the key enzymes that catalyse the skeleton formation of phaeosphspirone (Fig. S22 and S23). Thus, the biosynthetic pathway of phaeosphspirone is proposed as depicted in Scheme 1. First, SgpC (PKSs), SgpB/F and SgpA/G biosynthesize herbarin ( 2 ) similar to the fsr gene cluster forming fusarubin (
). Then, Baeyer-Villiger oxidation (SgpA or SgpG) leads herbarin ( 2 ) to produce compound ( 4 ), after which addition and dehydration (which might be spontaneous) form intermediate ( 5 ). Further oxidation (SgpE) of ( 5 ) at C-3 generates compound ( 6 ), and phaeosphspirone is finally formed by methylation (SgpB/F) of compound ( 6 ). The biosynthesis of phaeosphspirone is currently under investigation.

Herbarin ( 2 ) was reported to display biological activity against PC-3 M cell lines (
), whereas no report about bioactivities of O -methylherbarin ( 3 ) was found. The cytotoxic effects of compounds 1–3 were evaluated in three cancer cell lines, HepG2, HCT116, and B16 (
). Compounds 2 and 3 exhibited cytotoxic activity with IC 50 = 4.62 ± 0.55/3.64 ± 1.21, 2.56 ± 0.67/1.22 ± 0.18, and 2.25 ± 0.06/1.97 ± 0.32 μ M, respectively, compared with the positive control cis -platin (IC 50 =21.73 ±1.10, 9.71 ± 0.11, and 16.79 ± 2.85 μ M). Unfortunately, phaeosphspirone ( 1 / 1 ′ ) did not display cytotoxic effects.

